04210nam a22006495i 9780804788267DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202013cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2013010526  a97808047882677 a10.1515/97808047882672doi  a(DE-B1597)564315  a(OCoLC)1198930908  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aPN2039b.G585 2013 4aPN2039b.G585 2014 7aPER0110202bisacsh04a792.012231 aGobert, R. Darren, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Mind-Body Stage :bPassion and Interaction in the Cartesian Theater /cR. Darren Gobert. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note About Translations -- tPrologue: Another Cartesian Theater -- t1. Mind-Body Union; or, The Cartesian Ballet -- t2. Cartesian Plots, Dramatic Theory, and Emotional Wonder -- t3. Cartesian Acting; or, Interiors -- t4. Cartesian Design; or, Anatomies of the Theater -- tEpilogue: Cætera desunt -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDescartes's notion of subjectivity changed the way characters would be written, performed by actors, and received by audiences. His coordinate system reshaped how theatrical space would be conceived and built. His theory of the passions revolutionized our understanding of the emotional exchange between spectacle and spectators. Yet theater scholars have not seen Descartes's transformational impact on theater history. Nor have philosophers looked to this history to understand his reception and impact. After Descartes, playwrights put Cartesian characters on the stage and thematized their rational workings. Actors adapted their performances to account for new models of subjectivity and physiology. Critics theorized the theater's emotional and ethical benefits in Cartesian terms. Architects fostered these benefits by altering their designs. The Mind-Body Stage provides a dazzlingly original picture of one of the most consequential and confusing periods in the histories of modern theater and philosophy. Interdisciplinary and comparatist in scope, it uses methodological techniques from literary study, philosophy, theater history, and performance studies and draws on scores of documents (including letters, libretti, religious jeremiads, aesthetic treatises, and architectural plans) from several countries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aTheater and philosophyzEuropexHistoryy17th century. 0aTheater and philosophyzEuropexHistoryy18th century. 4aElisabeth of Bohemia. 4aPassions of the Soul. 4aacting theory. 4adramatic theory. 4adualism. 4amind-body union. 4aperformance. 4aphilosophy of theater. 4asubjectivity. 4atheater architecture. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Theater / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804788267zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804788267423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804788267.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles